321. The reading of the MSS. seems to require a dactyl—word unicus to constitute a foot, the third foot, a thing not sanctioned in trochaic metre, except at the beginning of the line or hemistich3 though this difficulty would be removed if we supposed umens-sum to form a word- group, like aeez'peclum &c The reading might also stand if unicus were here pronounced uncus, as aridus is on occasion pronounced ardus (Aac. 297 Fumea: ποθι aeque est ardus atque Ιιίε est senex). In Cas. 264 the reading of the MSS. points to Nihilo magis *zmeust <unicas est MSS.) ille‘ mihi filius quam eye rille? pater, but editors transpose ille vinz‘eust. Leo adopts C. F. Mueller's transposition, sum uniens. This however requires the very doubtful scansion patri (see Introd. iii. ξ 26). Schoell changes decere to decore Neut. of an Adj. deceris. Bentley suggested esse e re, which, if written ἴε ε νε, might easily become ecere and then decere. Tametsi is trisyllabic (if the reading be right) in a lyric passage, Pseud. 244 tam e'tsi oceupeim’s (bacchiac), but was apparently pronounced rather as a disyllable with accent on et, for in Plautus the normal metrical ictus is t(oem)e'tsz'. The Conjunction is normally followed by the Ind. in Plautus. (For Trin. 679 Facilest iuuenta : datur tynis tam e'tsz' ab inimico petas cf. note on v. 221 above.) Magis, followed by potius (v. 323).
